For 47 years,
he's been getting up at 5.45 am.

4
00:00:38,138 --> 00:00:39,901
By 6.20, he's already showered,

5
00:00:40,073 --> 00:00:42,007
and before 7.00,
he's bought the newspaper.

6
00:00:42,175 --> 00:00:43,233
He's a lawyer.
And he's my father.

7
00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:47,006
At 7.15, cafe latte and croissants.

8
00:00:47,180 --> 00:00:49,546
Perelman senior
thinks a man is free

9
00:00:49,883 --> 00:00:51,043
when he can have his breakfast

10
00:00:51,217 --> 00:00:54,118
and read the paper
without having to talk to anyone.

11
00:00:54,287 --> 00:00:58,155
Maybe even buy something,
but always in silence.

12
00:01:05,665 --> 00:01:09,101
At 7.30, he starts his rounds
in Court.

13
00:01:09,536 --> 00:01:12,369
He knows which courts to go to
first and which ones later.

14
00:01:12,539 --> 00:01:15,007
He knows the birthdays
and anniversarles

15
00:01:15,175 --> 00:01:18,110
of all the secretaries,
which candles they like,

16
00:01:18,311 --> 00:01:20,871
and the favorite soccer team
of the lift operator.

17
00:01:21,047 --> 00:01:23,572
Doctor!
There's some room here!

18
00:01:23,917 --> 00:01:26,147
I’ll be right back.

19
00:01:26,319 --> 00:01:27,650
Tizzles or Amelli?

20
00:01:27,987 --> 00:01:29,921
- Sand?
- Tizzles is injured.

21
00:01:30,090 --> 00:01:33,355
Sand, you think? The 4th floor?.
Marta's birthday. Court 8.

22
00:01:33,526 --> 00:01:35,653
- What about ''La Gata''?
- He was a crack in Racing...

23
00:01:35,995 --> 00:01:38,691
Dr. Perelman
doesn't stand in line

24
00:01:38,965 --> 00:01:41,695
and he's developed
his own system

25
00:01:41,868 --> 00:01:44,268
to avoid any kind of waiting.

26
00:02:09,996 --> 00:02:13,193
At 11.20, he takes a break
in an underground cafeteria.

27
00:02:13,366 --> 00:02:16,267
it’s time for a cheese
and tomato sandwich.

28
00:02:17,137 --> 00:02:19,230
Modesto is your husband?

29
00:02:19,405 --> 00:02:20,633
My partner.

30
00:02:21,774 --> 00:02:25,301
That's fine. It's just a detail.

31
00:02:25,778 --> 00:02:29,236
He uses those fifteen minutes
to meet with a client.

32
00:02:29,415 --> 00:02:32,316
He says some of them
are intimidated by offices...

33
00:02:32,685 --> 00:02:34,516
That's why there are some clients
for the cafe

34
00:02:34,687 --> 00:02:35,676
and others for the office.

35
00:02:36,022 --> 00:02:37,148
Tell me.

36
00:02:37,690 --> 00:02:40,215
What are you growing now?
Is it broccoli?

37
00:02:40,493 --> 00:02:42,393
They took out the gear box before...

38
00:02:42,562 --> 00:02:46,430
Perelman
is a Zelig among lawyers.

39
00:02:47,433 --> 00:02:49,628
He immediately picks up
the speech,

40
00:02:49,802 --> 00:02:51,929
manners and semantics
of his clients.

41
00:02:52,105 --> 00:02:55,370
He likes to see them
in their natural habitat.

42
00:02:55,775 --> 00:02:58,141
A leak here...
I’ll take out the gear box.

43
00:02:58,311 --> 00:02:59,369
Have a mate.

44
00:02:59,812 --> 00:03:01,643
Not on purpose.
That's just the way he is.

45
00:03:01,814 --> 00:03:05,375
He knows a bit about every trade.

46
00:03:05,718 --> 00:03:07,117
I heard your message.

47
00:03:07,287 --> 00:03:09,050
She's Norita.

48
00:03:09,222 --> 00:03:12,089
She's been dad's secretary
since mom died.

49
00:03:12,258 --> 00:03:13,589
She earns 860 pesos a month,

50
00:03:13,760 --> 00:03:17,753
but Perelman
always rounds it up to 1,000.

51
00:03:18,665 --> 00:03:21,065
She arrives at 3.30
and leaves at 8.45 pm,

52
00:03:21,467 --> 00:03:23,594
the same routine
or the last 15 years.

53
00:03:27,440 --> 00:03:30,568
Ever since l can remember,
the ''R'' has been missing here.

54
00:03:30,743 --> 00:03:33,371
But Perelman says
people understand it anyway.

55
00:03:35,181 --> 00:03:38,275
Norita and l get along well,
but l don't know much about her.

56
00:03:38,451 --> 00:03:40,180
l saw her outside the office once.

57
00:03:40,353 --> 00:03:42,548
At a funeral. Very uncomfortable.

58
00:03:42,722 --> 00:03:46,055
Sometimes it's uncomfortable
to see people out of context.

59
00:03:51,598 --> 00:03:52,565
Any news?

60
00:03:52,732 --> 00:03:55,496
Ms. Ducatti called twice.

61
00:03:55,735 --> 00:03:58,067
You have a sore throat?

62
00:03:58,238 --> 00:04:00,069
No big deal.

63
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:02,731
I didn't know
what to wear today.

64
00:04:03,076 --> 00:04:05,169
I couldn’t decide: raincoat or...

65
00:04:05,478 --> 00:04:07,503
The decoration of the office
is representative of dad's taste,

66
00:04:08,147 --> 00:04:11,139
which is actually a combination
of all his clients' taste.

67
00:04:12,218 --> 00:04:13,776
There's also
a second bathroom

68
00:04:14,120 --> 00:04:15,815
doubling as an archive
and a kitchen.

69
00:04:17,423 --> 00:04:19,414
A meeting room
where nobody ever met.

70
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:21,488
Did the form arrive?

71
00:04:21,794 --> 00:04:24,024
And the heart of the firm.<i>:</i>
the attorney's office.

72
00:04:26,866 --> 00:04:28,299
Why a kettle?

73
00:04:28,468 --> 00:04:32,336
I went by a store
and saw this electric kettle,

74
00:04:32,839 --> 00:04:36,240
and you can boll water,
for tea, mate...

75
00:04:43,449 --> 00:04:46,646
And this is the second office.
it was supposed to be for me.

76
00:04:46,819 --> 00:04:47,786
But it's not.

77
00:04:47,954 --> 00:04:50,718
in this firm, there's no place
for another Perelman.

78
00:04:54,494 --> 00:04:57,691
...and that's why the evidence,
in a penal Lawsuit...

79
00:04:57,864 --> 00:05:01,231
That's me, Mr. Perelman.
Also a lawyer.

80
00:05:01,401 --> 00:05:03,869
But l didn't go for Law.
l went for Justice.

81
00:05:04,203 --> 00:05:06,262
Right now I’m lecturing.

82
00:05:06,439 --> 00:05:08,532
At this hour,
l mostly get young girls,

83
00:05:08,841 --> 00:05:11,139
and they dress so well
it barely seems like 7 am.

84
00:05:11,577 --> 00:05:13,340
But we don't notice that.

85
00:05:13,513 --> 00:05:15,640
At night it's different.
There are bearded men

86
00:05:15,815 --> 00:05:17,715
who will never graduate.

87
00:05:17,884 --> 00:05:21,149
...or in American movies
about lawyers.

88
00:05:21,321 --> 00:05:22,686
Or in much-talked about cases,

89
00:05:22,855 --> 00:05:26,484
Like the recent one
about the pop singer

90
00:05:26,659 --> 00:05:29,025
accused
of sexually abusing minors,

91
00:05:29,195 --> 00:05:31,629
sleeping with kids, you know.

92
00:05:31,831 --> 00:05:35,767
In this case, the Jury decides
whether he's guilty or innocent,

93
00:05:35,935 --> 00:05:38,904
without the need
to substantiate anything.

94
00:05:40,606 --> 00:05:42,631
Hi, I'm from the Students' Union.

95
00:05:43,643 --> 00:05:44,940
I don't know if you're aware

96
00:05:45,278 --> 00:05:48,611
of the near extinction of
the Emperor Penguin in our country.

97
00:05:48,781 --> 00:05:51,682
We're collecting signatures
to put an end to it.

98
00:05:51,851 --> 00:05:57,187
You can sign outside.
I'm from the Ecology Commission.

99
00:05:57,357 --> 00:05:59,723
Please, do sign.
Today, it's the penguins,

100
00:05:59,892 --> 00:06:01,484
tomorrow, it could be us.

101
00:06:01,661 --> 00:06:02,821
Let's all make a commitment.

102
00:06:02,995 --> 00:06:07,295
Could you come back after class?
We don't have enough time now.

103
00:06:07,467 --> 00:06:09,367
Who the fuck are you
to kick me out?

104
00:06:09,535 --> 00:06:12,868
I'm the professor in charge here.

105
00:06:13,840 --> 00:06:15,671
You are Perelman.

106
00:06:17,443 --> 00:06:19,775
Don't you remember me?
You fuck up people’s lives!

107
00:06:20,713 --> 00:06:21,702
I never graduated
because of you!

108
00:06:21,881 --> 00:06:22,973
What did I do to you?

109
00:06:23,516 --> 00:06:26,349
What do you do for people,
Perelman?

110
00:06:27,587 --> 00:06:30,920
- We'd appreciate it if you left now.
- Faggot!

111
00:06:34,594 --> 00:06:36,653
Let's pretend nothing happened.

112
00:06:36,829 --> 00:06:39,389
Or better yet, let's pretend
something did happen.

113
00:06:41,300 --> 00:06:43,860
Tell me
what that man was wearing.

114
00:06:44,036 --> 00:06:46,869
A tracksuit
or brown corduroy?

115
00:06:47,039 --> 00:06:49,507
-A tracksuit, I think.
-A tracksuit?

116
00:06:49,675 --> 00:06:50,937
But I think it was brown.

117
00:06:51,277 --> 00:06:52,767
You think it was brown.

118
00:06:52,945 --> 00:06:56,676
Did he put his hands on the desk?

119
00:06:56,849 --> 00:06:58,441
Yes, both hands, I believe.

120
00:06:58,618 --> 00:07:00,347
Are you positive?

121
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:02,753
You're not sure, are you?

122
00:07:03,523 --> 00:07:08,358
Could you describe
the state that man was in?

123
00:07:08,528 --> 00:07:09,620
He seemed half-crazy.

124
00:07:09,796 --> 00:07:12,890
Half-crazy
or three-quarters-crazy?

125
00:07:13,433 --> 00:07:17,995
In any case, he wouldn’t be
totally crazy. Tough one, right?

126
00:07:19,338 --> 00:07:23,331
Where did he take
the pamphlets from?

127
00:07:23,810 --> 00:07:24,970
From an army satchel.

128
00:07:25,311 --> 00:07:27,779
From an army satchel?
Army-brown?

129
00:07:27,947 --> 00:07:30,415
Army-green, Left-hand side.

130
00:07:30,583 --> 00:07:31,914
Good eyesight.
He was pretty far away.

131
00:07:33,519 --> 00:07:35,510
l have a student named Sandra.

132
00:07:35,688 --> 00:07:39,419
The only first name l remember.
The rest are just last names.

133
00:07:39,592 --> 00:07:43,494
She sits in the back,
as if trying to be invisible.

134
00:07:43,663 --> 00:07:45,790
impossible.
Sandra will be my wife.

135
00:07:45,965 --> 00:07:48,024
Not now that she's a student.

136
00:07:48,367 --> 00:07:51,768
But l enjoy her listening to me.
That motivates me.

137
00:07:51,938 --> 00:07:55,874
Every day, judges decide
based on testimonies...

138
00:07:56,042 --> 00:07:59,773
from witnesses
as accurate or inaccurate as you.

139
00:07:59,946 --> 00:08:02,915
And the destines of many people
depend on those witnesses.

140
00:08:03,649 --> 00:08:07,016
Tell me
what that man sold to me.

141
00:08:08,421 --> 00:08:09,479
Come on, give it a try.

142
00:08:09,655 --> 00:08:10,986
Faggot.

143
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:12,484
Faggot or maggot?

144
00:08:12,658 --> 00:08:15,422
- Faggot.
- So he did...

145
00:08:16,963 --> 00:08:18,988
Is calling someone a faggot
a crime?

146
00:08:19,932 --> 00:08:21,092
Tough one, I know...

147
00:08:22,335 --> 00:08:25,566
But the following day Sandra didn't
come to class. Nor the day after.

148
00:08:31,844 --> 00:08:33,971
You know the address?

149
00:08:36,782 --> 00:08:38,773
That one or this one?

150
00:08:39,085 --> 00:08:40,109
That one.

151
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:42,553
- The fitting room?
- Sure.

152
00:08:42,722 --> 00:08:45,623
- Does it suit you?
- It's OK, I Like a loose fit.

153
00:08:45,791 --> 00:08:47,418
You want me to take a look?

154
00:08:47,593 --> 00:08:49,652
No, it's perfect. I’ll take it.

155
00:08:53,900 --> 00:08:58,064
it turned out we were colleagues.
She was also into teaching.

156
00:08:58,404 --> 00:09:00,599
She was a Pilates instructor.

157
00:09:00,773 --> 00:09:03,901
- I changed before coming.
- Great.

158
00:09:04,777 --> 00:09:07,075
Taking a few classes
seemed like the best excuse.

159
00:09:07,413 --> 00:09:09,938
Or perhaps, it wasn't.

160
00:09:11,617 --> 00:09:13,881
The first class
was somewhat uncomfortable.

161
00:09:14,587 --> 00:09:16,748
Until a few days ago,
l was Mr. Perelman,

162
00:09:16,923 --> 00:09:19,153
high up on the pedestal
of knowledge.

163
00:09:19,492 --> 00:09:23,053
And now l was just a body
starting its decline.

164
00:09:24,564 --> 00:09:26,122
That's it, we start relaxing...

165
00:09:26,465 --> 00:09:30,492
She showed me how to breathe
and tighten my belly and thighs.

166
00:09:30,670 --> 00:09:33,764
Let your waist relax....
And then expand...

167
00:09:33,940 --> 00:09:36,602
We were alone,
but pretended not to notice.

168
00:09:36,776 --> 00:09:41,179
We only talked about things
related to the posture of my back.

169
00:09:41,981 --> 00:09:44,609
- It feels good, right?
- Yeah.

170
00:09:44,984 --> 00:09:48,442
- Like this?
- Yes, let it go... Like that.

171
00:09:50,022 --> 00:09:52,991
Well, I think
that's enough for today.

172
00:09:53,159 --> 00:09:55,389
That is... if you agree.

173
00:09:57,930 --> 00:09:59,158
Excuse me.

174
00:10:01,467 --> 00:10:02,957
When the class was over,

175
00:10:03,135 --> 00:10:06,935
l felt an irrepressible desire
to put on my suit and be normal.

176
00:10:19,919 --> 00:10:22,752
Each time we exhale,
we feel more relaxed.

177
00:10:22,922 --> 00:10:25,083
And we really enjoy it,

178
00:10:25,257 --> 00:10:29,489
as we feel the back relaxing.

179
00:10:31,030 --> 00:10:33,897
Now I’ll pull you
and you just Let yourself go.

180
00:10:37,136 --> 00:10:38,433
Now... exhale.

181
00:10:43,509 --> 00:10:46,910
At first, l felt Sandra touched me
in a special way.

182
00:10:47,079 --> 00:10:48,774
But the method itself

183
00:10:48,948 --> 00:10:52,008
involved special care
for all its students.

184
00:10:58,190 --> 00:11:01,990
After a short while,
Sandra dropped out of school,

185
00:11:02,161 --> 00:11:04,152
so l had to keep going
to her place,

186
00:11:04,330 --> 00:11:06,093
trapped in her Pilates world.

187
00:11:06,265 --> 00:11:08,392
it was the only way
to keep in touch.

188
00:11:17,176 --> 00:11:18,700
l never dared tell her anything.

189
00:11:19,045 --> 00:11:21,013
You can't declare
your love to a woman

190
00:11:21,180 --> 00:11:23,705
while you're sweating
and tightening your thighs.

191
00:11:24,050 --> 00:11:26,416
But l started
doing the exercises better,

192
00:11:26,585 --> 00:11:29,554
and took the air
to any part of the body.

193
00:11:29,722 --> 00:11:31,622
Through the nose, I know.

194
00:11:33,225 --> 00:11:34,351
Through the nose...

195
00:11:35,261 --> 00:11:39,061
Joseph Pilates was once
a prisoner in a concentration camp.

196
00:11:39,231 --> 00:11:41,222
He wanted to strengthen
his comrades' muscles.

197
00:11:41,400 --> 00:11:43,595
But he only had springs
from mattresses...

198
00:11:43,769 --> 00:11:45,760
And without realizing it,

199
00:11:45,938 --> 00:11:49,032
he started developing
the Pilates Method.

200
00:11:53,646 --> 00:11:55,409
Let me show you something.

201
00:11:59,085 --> 00:12:01,076
This is right, and this is wrong.

202
00:12:01,253 --> 00:12:02,777
- This is wrong?
- Yeah.

203
00:12:03,789 --> 00:12:06,314
It seemed perfect to me.

204
00:12:07,526 --> 00:12:08,993
It's cold.

205
00:12:09,328 --> 00:12:11,728
- It's iced tea.
- It's meant to be cold?

206
00:12:21,340 --> 00:12:23,103
You stand Like this.

207
00:12:23,275 --> 00:12:25,334
Yeah, maybe...

208
00:12:25,644 --> 00:12:27,703
No, you stand Like this.

209
00:12:28,047 --> 00:12:29,275
You have to stand Like that.

210
00:12:29,448 --> 00:12:32,042
But that's going
to take me a while.

211
00:12:33,119 --> 00:12:36,282
Isn't it a bit painful
to stand Like that?

212
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:39,050
Which one is yours?

213
00:12:39,225 --> 00:12:42,558
Luckily, one day Sandra had
a little problem with the Law.

214
00:12:42,728 --> 00:12:46,220
And l was able to take her out
of her world, to a safer place.

215
00:12:47,066 --> 00:12:50,194
Please be careful.
They are very fragile.

216
00:12:51,170 --> 00:12:52,660
The springs are imported.

217
00:12:52,838 --> 00:12:55,432
- Don't you worry.
- Thank you.

218
00:12:57,176 --> 00:12:58,837
- This one is for you.
- OK.

219
00:13:00,446 --> 00:13:02,607
Good morning. How are you doing?
I'm Dr. Perelman.

220
00:13:02,782 --> 00:13:06,741
A lawyer in a tracksuit?
That's weird. Excuse me.

221
00:13:08,687 --> 00:13:10,052
What happened?

222
00:13:12,158 --> 00:13:14,718
Sandra had a problem with
the Law of Trademarks and Patents.

223
00:13:15,528 --> 00:13:18,429
The Pilates Method
was registered by a company

224
00:13:18,597 --> 00:13:20,861
with the rights
for the entire country.

225
00:13:21,200 --> 00:13:23,191
Poor thing, she was desperate.

226
00:13:23,369 --> 00:13:27,169
She thought it was like
teaching swimming or music.

227
00:13:27,907 --> 00:13:31,809
It's not going to be fast,
It's not going to be easy, but...

228
00:13:40,886 --> 00:13:42,877
Defense Lawyer for the Poor
Office No. 5

229
00:14:07,313 --> 00:14:11,909
l didn't know where to start.
l could tell right from wrong,

230
00:14:12,251 --> 00:14:14,481
but not what the Law
could do for Sandra.

231
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:17,780
l went to see Perelman senior
at Astorga's pizza place.

232
00:14:17,957 --> 00:14:20,482
He's a client
with many restaurants downtown,

233
00:14:20,659 --> 00:14:23,219
always in trouble
...hygiene problems.

234
00:14:23,395 --> 00:14:28,230
Here it says they took a sample of
spaghetti sauce with live insects.

235
00:14:28,801 --> 00:14:30,234
Your own employee
signed as a witness.

236
00:14:30,402 --> 00:14:32,131
But I also kept a sample.

237
00:14:33,973 --> 00:14:35,907
The guy is always in trouble

238
00:14:36,242 --> 00:14:38,642
so he pays dad a fixed fee
to deal with the law.

239
00:14:38,811 --> 00:14:41,302
And dad also gets to eat for free.

240
00:14:41,814 --> 00:14:44,806
As Perelman senior says.<i>:</i>
in the end, it all adds up.

241
00:14:48,888 --> 00:14:52,722
He drafted the writ on a
tissue napkin that l still keep.

242
00:14:52,892 --> 00:14:56,328
We didn't have to pay for dinner.
Astorga treated me too.

243
00:14:56,795 --> 00:15:00,287
Can you heat it up?
But, please, not in the microwave.

244
00:15:00,466 --> 00:15:02,764
- What are you drinking?
- Just water.

245
00:15:05,738 --> 00:15:08,798
Before being a prisoner
in a concentration camp,

